<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1893,2028]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,153,611]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="105" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,434,1893,1920]" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Genus-level characters.</emphasis>
Medium-sized (
<quantity box="[623,720,1894,1920]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="104" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
long), light-brown phorid flies. Males (
<figureCitation box="[1181,1265,1894,1920]" captionStart="FIGURES 1" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1340,1365]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,317,1315]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,309,1315]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1A–B. Habitus, Epicnemis species. a. E. ratanae new species, male. b. Epicnemis species, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908051/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
): Frontal setae reclinate, dorsal fronto-orbital setae absent, thus most species with 4-2-4 frontal setae and one pair of supra-antennal seta (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[266,348,1966,1992]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–23" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1624,1649]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,183,1596]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[172,1415,181,1598]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 18–23. Heads, Epicnemis species, males, anterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908057/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
), although first row often not in straight line (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[922,1006,1966,1992]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–23" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1624,1649]" captionTargetBox="[173,1415,183,1596]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[172,1415,181,1598]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 18–23. Heads, Epicnemis species, males, anterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908057/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). Median furrow absent. Ommatrichia present. Flagellomere 1 yellowish-orange, pyriform; arista dorsal. Palpus large, yellowish-orange, with thick black setae apically and thinner, shorter black setulae ventrally. Postpronotal lobes large, spiracle nearly dorsal (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1424,153,179]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–35" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1741,1766]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,276,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,273,1717]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 30–35. Epicnemis species, males. Figs. 30–33. Heads, anterior view. Fig. 34. Anterior part of thorax, lateral. Fig. 35. Male terminalia, left lateral. Abbreviation: sp, spiracle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908061/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
). Posterior margin of anepisternum darkened. Parapsidal suture (between scutum and anepisternum) short, not extending anteriorly to spiracle. Anepisternum setulose dorsally. Notopleuron with 3 large setae. Anepimeron reduced, meron expanded, concave. Halter short. Costal setae short; wing vein R2+3 absent. Midtibia with setal palisade extending to midlength. Hind tibia with several scattered medium-sized anterodorsal setae and complete dorsal setal palisade. Eversible membrane bearing field of dense thickened setulae present in between tergite 1 and 2 (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 36–39" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1664,1689]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,671,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,669,1639]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 36–39. Epicnemis species. Figs. 36–37. Male terminalia, left lateral. Fig. 36. Air dried. Fig. 37. HMDS dried. Figs. 38–39. Posterior part of thorax and anterior segments of male abdomen, dorsal. Fig. 38. habitus. Fig. 39. detail of spinuli. Abbreviation: T1, T2—abdominal tergite 1, 2." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908063/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">Figs. 39</figureCitation>
–40); smaller such fields present more posteriorly. Hypandrium greatly reduced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,153,611]" box="[199,623,405,432]" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">
Females: apterous, limuloid (
<figureCitation box="[526,608,405,432]" captionStart="FIGURES 1" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1340,1365]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,317,1315]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,309,1315]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1A–B. Habitus, Epicnemis species. a. E. ratanae new species, male. b. Epicnemis species, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908051/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">Fig. 1b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
