<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="106" pageId="2" pageNumber="105" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,153,611]" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,434,512,539]" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">Species recognition.</emphasis>
The most distinctive characters for these flies are found in the male genitalia and the frons. Most species are recognizable easily by observing these two features. The genitalia are often withdrawn into the abdomen, however, making dissection a frequent necessity.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908053" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3908053" box="[151,705,1974,1999]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908053/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="105" startId="2.[151,250,1974,1999]" targetBox="[153,1435,639,1949]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,705,1974,1999]" box="[151,705,1974,1999]" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1974,1999]" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
Known distribution of 
<taxonomicName box="[513,619,1975,1998]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Epicnemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[513,619,1975,1998]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">Epicnemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,612]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
Setation of the frons and of the legs is often used in phorid taxonomy, but in 
<taxonomicName box="[1051,1168,154,179]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Epicnemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1051,1168,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Epicnemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the patterns of setae are notably varied and less reliable. The species with larger numbers of specimens invariably include those with extra frontal setae, or in one case (an atypical male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gonzalez &amp; Häggqvist, 2020" authorityName="Gonzalez &amp; Häggqvist" authorityYear="2020" box="[706,785,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Epicnemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alus" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[706,785,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. alus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[793,933,225,252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
), lacking usual frontal setae. Tibial setae are similarly varied in individual specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,612]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,339,296,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Way of life.</emphasis>
With their limuoid female body forms, these flies presumably live in the nests of termites. Surprisingly, there is no specific information on hosts or lifestyles. Their larvae might be predators, scavengers, or parasitoids.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,612]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,404,431]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Distribution.</emphasis>
Oriental Region (
<figureCitation box="[560,661,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1974,1999]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,639,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[152,1435,633,1949]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Known distribution of Epicnemis species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3908053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3908053/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Figure 2</figureCitation>
). This genus conforms well to Wallace’s Line (
<bibRefCitation author="Wallace, A. R." box="[1204,1365,405,432]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" refId="ref17087" refString="Wallace, A. R. (1876) The geographical distribution of animals with a study of relations of living and extinct fauans as elucidating the past changes of the earth's surface with maps and illustrations. Vols. 1 &amp; 2. MacMillan, London, 503 + 607 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 46581" type="book" year="1876">Wallace 1876</bibRefCitation>
), with species being apparently absent from 
<collectingRegion box="[575,676,441,467]" country="Indonesia" name="Sulawesi Utara" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Sulawesi</collectingRegion>
(at least not reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[957,1104,440,467]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="139 - 141" refId="ref16845" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1985) Watching scuttle flies on Project Wallace. Antenna, 9, 139 - 141." type="journal article" year="1985">Disney 1985</bibRefCitation>
). Russell Cox (personal communication) has reported specimens from Timor, however, which is east of the southern extremity of Wallace’s line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,612]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,437,548,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Derivation of name.</emphasis>
The name seems to be based on the presence of mid- and hind tibial setal palisades (
<emphasis box="[1393,1427,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">epi</emphasis>
- upon, 
<emphasis box="[221,293,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">kneme</emphasis>
- knee), a character that Borgmeier stressed in his original description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
